    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>In my case the signature of the method that I want to capture its argument is:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>public byte[] write(byte ... data) throws IOException;\n</code></pre>\n<p>In this case you should cast to <strong>byte array</strong> explicitly:</p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>when(spi.write((byte[])anyVararg())).thenReturn(someValue);\n</code></pre>\n<p>I'm using mockito version <code>1.10.19</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 27004,
      "reputation" : 29201,
      "user_id" : 70795,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 56,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/fe85bc40e37968d4ea24785740f5da6a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Mark",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/70795/mark"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 9,
    "last_activity_date" : 1479115568,
    "creation_date" : 1479115568,
    "answer_id" : 40585388,
    "question_id" : 2631596,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I have been using the code in Peter Westmacott's answer however with Mockito 2.2.15 you can now do the following:</p>\n\n<p><code>verify(a).method(100L, arg1, arg2, arg3)</code></p>\n\n<p>where <code>arg1, arg2, arg3</code> are varargs.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 319999,
      "reputation" : 936,
      "user_id" : 638048,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/97211c4044dd3fad021cec914a9c087c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Richard Whitehead",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/638048/richard-whitehead"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1486729244,
    "creation_date" : 1486729244,
    "answer_id" : 42159276,
    "question_id" : 2631596,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You can also loop over the arguments:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Object[] args = invocation.getArguments(); \nfor( int argNo = 0; argNo &lt; args.length; ++argNo) { \n    // ... do something with args[argNo] \n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>for example check their types and cast them appropriately, add to a list or whatever.</p>\n"
  }, {
